## Notifications and Email Sending - FQ Source

Goal: Consistent process to add in-app notifications and optionally send emails for those notifications.

### Database model (public)
- `notification_events` (one row per event):
  - `scope`: 'user' | 'company' | 'global'
    - user → set `user_id` (auth.users.id)
    - company → set `company_id` (public.company.id)
    - global → no `user_id`/`company_id`
  - `type`: business type (e.g., 'rfx_sent_for_review')
  - `title`, `body`
  - `target_type`, `target_id`, `target_url` (optional deep link)
  - `delivery_channel`: 'in_app' | 'email' | 'both'
  - RLS “Users can view applicable notifications”: users see global, their direct, or their company notifications.

- `notification_user_state` (per user-event state):
  - `user_id`: auth.users.id (default auth.uid())
  - `is_read`, `read_at`
  - `is_reviewed`, `reviewed_at`
  - `is_archived`, `archived_at`
  - Unique (notification_id, user_id); RLS self-only.
  - If no row exists: default interpretation → unread, unreviewed, unarchived.

### Add a new notification (in code)
Set scope, content, and delivery channel. Examples:

```ts
// Insert a direct notification to one user (in-app only)
await supabase
  .from('notification_events')
  .insert({
    scope: 'user',
    user_id: someAuthUserId,     // auth.users.id
    type: 'example_event',
    title: 'Action required',
    body: 'Please review your settings.',
    target_url: '/settings',
    delivery_channel: 'in_app'
  });
```

```ts
// Notification to all users in a company, email + in-app
await supabase
  .from('notification_events')
  .insert({
    scope: 'company',
    company_id: companyId,
    type: 'company_update',
    title: 'New policy',
    body: 'A new policy is available for review.',
    target_url: '/my-company',
    delivery_channel: 'both'
  });
```

### Send the email for a notification (generic)
We have a generic Edge Function: `send-notification-email`
- Subject: `FQ Source: {title}`
- Body: Explains there is a new notification, includes `title` and `body`
- Button: always points to `https://app.fqsource.com`
- Recipients resolved by scope:
  - user → that user
  - company → all users in the company (via `app_user.auth_user_id`)
  - global → all users (use with caution)

Usage examples:
```ts
// Method 1: By notification ID(s) - use when you have the IDs
await supabase.functions.invoke('send-notification-email', {
  body: { notificationId: 'uuid-here' }
});

await supabase.functions.invoke('send-notification-email', {
  body: { notificationIds: [id1, id2, id3] }
});

// Method 2: By filter (RECOMMENDED for DB triggers) - uses service role to bypass RLS
await supabase.functions.invoke('send-notification-email', {
  body: { 
    type: 'rfx_announcement_posted',
    targetType: 'rfx',
    targetId: rfxId
  }
});
```

Notes:
- The function uses Resend with `RESEND_API_KEY`. Deploy with:
  - `supabase functions deploy send-notification-email --no-verify-jwt`
- **Method 2 (filter)** is preferred when calling from client code after DB triggers because it uses service role key and bypasses RLS
- Add a small delay (500ms) before calling to ensure trigger has executed

### UI behaviors (reference)
- Sidebar bell shows unread count (not archived, not read). Opening the dropdown marks listed notifications as read (via RPC).
- Notifications Center allows marking reviewed and archive/unarchive; “Show archived” toggles archived visibility.

### Automated notifications (DB triggers)
When creating DB triggers to auto-generate notifications:

**IMPORTANT - Common pitfalls:**
1. ⚠️ Always use `AFTER INSERT` (not `BEFORE` or `INSTEAD OF`)
2. ⚠️ Use `SECURITY DEFINER` to bypass RLS and access all related data
3. ⚠️ The `app_user` table does NOT have an `email` column (it's in `auth.users`)
4. ⚠️ Always include `RAISE NOTICE` for debugging in production
5. ⚠️ Wrap notifications INSERT in exception handler to not fail the original operation

**Example trigger function structure:**
```sql
create or replace function public.create_notifications_on_event()
returns trigger
language plpgsql
security definer  -- Important: bypasses RLS
set search_path = public
as $$
declare
  v_notifications_created int;
begin
  -- Always check operation type
  if tg_op <> 'INSERT' then
    return new;
  end if;

  -- Insert notifications (query will use SECURITY DEFINER permissions)
  insert into public.notification_events (scope, company_id, type, title, body, ...)
  select 'company', company_id, 'event_type', 'Title', 'Body', ...
  from related_table
  where conditions;

  get diagnostics v_notifications_created = row_count;
  raise notice 'Notifications created: %', v_notifications_created;

  return new;  -- Always return new
exception
  when others then
    raise warning 'Error creating notifications: %', sqlerrm;
    return new;  -- Don't fail the original operation
end;
$$;

-- Create the trigger (AFTER INSERT, not INSTEAD OF)
create trigger trg_name
after insert on table_name  -- AFTER, not INSTEAD OF
for each row
execute function public.create_notifications_on_event();
```

**Existing notification types in the system:**
- `rfx_sent_for_review` - RFX sent for approval
- `rfx_approved` - RFX approved by admin
- `company_rfx_invitation` - Company invited to RFX
- `supplier_accepted_invitation` - Supplier accepted RFX invitation
- `supplier_signed_nda` - Supplier signed NDA
- `nda_validated` - NDA validated by buyer
- `supplier_document_uploaded` - Supplier uploaded document (proposal/offer)
- `rfx_announcement_posted` - New announcement posted in RFX

### Security and RLS
- `notification_events` RLS ensures users only see relevant notifications.
- `notification_user_state` RLS is self-only.
- Company scope uses `app_user.auth_user_id = auth.uid()` to resolve membership.
- Trigger functions use `SECURITY DEFINER` to bypass RLS and access all related data.

